05166nam a22009375i 9780231543156DE-B159720190516114113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190516s2017    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315431567 a10.7312/shel178222doi  a(DE-B1597)481777  a(OCoLC)966591003  a(OCoLC)979575569  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPR888.L69bS457 2019 7aLIT0040202bisacsh 7aLIT0041302bisacsh 7aLIT0041602bisacsh04a823.085092231 aShelden, Ashley, eauthor.10aUnmaking Love :bThe Contemporary Novel and the Impossibility of Union /cAshley Shelden. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLiterature Now00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Unmaking Love -- t1. Lesbian Fantasy: Psychoanalysis, the Legacy of Modernist Love, and Djuna Barnes's Nightwood -- t2. The Ends of Love: Amorous Redemption, the Passion for Negativity, James Joyce's Ulysses, and Hanif Kureishi's Intimacy -- t3. Amorous Time: Nostalgia, Temporality, and the Pursuit of Optimism in Alan Hollinghurst's Th e Line of Beauty -- t4. Cosmopolitan Love: Encountering Difference in Hari Kunzru's Transmission and Kazuo Ishiguro's The Unconsoled -- tConclusion: Otherness, Cloud Atlas , and Contemporary Literature -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex  aThe contemporary novel does more than revise our conception of love-it explodes it, queers it, and makes it unrecognizable. Rather than providing union, connection, and completion, love in contemporary fiction destroys the possibility of unity, harbors negativity, and foregrounds difference. Comparing contemporary and modernist depictions of love to delineate critical continuities and innovations, Unmaking Love locates queerness in the novelistic strategies of Ian McEwan, Zadie Smith, Hanif Kureshi, Alan Hollinghurst, and Hari Kunzru. In their work, "queer love" becomes more than shorthand for sexual identity. It comes to embody thwarted expectations, disarticulated organization, and unnerving multiplicity. In queer love, social forms are deformed, affective bonds do not bind, and social structures threaten to come undone. Unmaking Love draws on psychoanalysis and gender and sexuality studies to read love's role in contemporary literature and its relation to queer negativity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 16. Mai 2019) 0aEnglish fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish fictiony21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aIntimacy (Psychology) in literature. 0aLove in literature. 0aModernism (Literature)zGreat Britain. 70(DE-601)1041376810(DE-588)4047497-5aProsa2gnd 70(DE-601)1057535560(DE-588)4123655-5aLiebegMotiv2gnd 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / LGBT.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2016-2018z978311066255908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2017z978311065472108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017z978311054330808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2017z9783110548198oZDB-23-DKU40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/shel17822423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231543156.jpg  a978-3-11-054330-8  CUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017b2017  a978-3-11-062526-4  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017b2017  a978-3-11-065472-1  CUP eBook Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-066255-9  CUP eBook Package 2016-2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEB